<div class="m-6 p-6 max-w-auto mx-auto bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md space-x-4">
 <h3 class="text-2xl">Results</h3>
 <h4 class="text-xl">First Hypothesis</h4>
  <p>
    In fact all companies’ stock is at least slightly corelated to the mentions of the respective company on Twitter. 
      Although the correlation in the case of <a href="/alphabet">Alphabet</a> is minimal (approx. 0.087), it is still there.
      This leads to the conclusion that this hypothesis can be regarded as true.
  </p>
  <h4 class="text-xl">Second Hypothesis</h4>
  <p>
    Reviewing the correlations calculated, this hypothesis can suprisingly not be validated. <a href="/telsa">Tesla</a>, with a correlation of approx. -0.102, resides at the lower end of the spectrum.
  </p>
  <h4 class="text-xl">Third Hypothesis</h4>
  <p>
    This last hypothesis can also not be validated since in the dataset aquired <a href="/apple">Apple</a> has the biggest correlation out of all of the companies tested with approx. 0.411. 
    This was surprising since <a href="/apple">Apple</a> traditionally tries to keep a lower profile in social media. However, these results seem to make sense as <a href="/apple">Apple</a> also frequently provokes with expensive 
    monitor stands or 25$ cleaning coths. The longer I think about it the more it makes sense. <a href="/apple">Apple</a> has used the public outcry about products like these quiet often in the past to get additional publicity 
    for their other products (they actually want to sell).
  </p>
